  <h2>Goddard's Market: West-Side Growth and USD 265 Appeal</h2>
  <p>Goddard's along I-54/Kellogg on Wichita's west side, sitting at the edge of Wichita's expansion. You get a mix of established 1970s-1990s neighborhoods and newer growth pushing west. USD 265 is a consistently top-rated school district, which attracts growing families. That school reputation means steady buyer demand for good homes, but it also means when someone sells, families are paying attention.</p>
  <p>Goddard is about $160k-$280k mostly — not as expensive as Andover, not as affordable as Haysville. It's a sweet spot for families who want good schools, reasonable prices, and still be close to Wichita jobs. Easy I-54 access is a major draw.</p>

  <h2>Goddard Housing and Market Reality</h2>
  <p>Goddard's got a lot of 1970s-1990s established homes mixed with newer construction as Wichita expands. USD 265 school district pulls families who prioritize education. Price range is $160k-$280k. Homes in established areas are solid ranch and post-war construction with good bones but aging systems. Newer subdivisions are more modern, better systems, move-in-ready condition.</p>
  <p>The school district reputation is powerful — families will pay a bit more to be in USD 265 boundaries. That makes the market stable for sellers with good homes, but it also means buyers are looking carefully.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Goddard</h2>
  <p>Growing families who bought, raised kids, and now need more space — they need to sell the old house fast so they can buy bigger. Relocations for job changes. People moving to the area for work who need a quick exit from Goddard. Estate sales from original Goddard homeowners aging out. Divorce situations. Landlords managing rental properties in school-district areas. People who bought in Goddard for the schools, situation changed, and they need to move.</p>

